{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486718"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:42:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"162"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/162"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.11,0.67,0,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31579"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/28749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department after sustaining a fall at home. On assessment, she has poor coordination and falls to the right when unsupported. She is dysphagic and her voice is hoarse. She also has decreased pain and temperature sensation of the right side of the face and the left side of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior alternating hemiplegia (Weber syndrome)","Medial medullary syndrome (of Dejerine)","Lateral medullary syndrome (of Wallenberg)","Locked-in syndrome","Spinal cord hemisection (Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with crossed signs including cranial nerve deficits, suggesting a lesion of the brainstem. This particular constellation of deficits corresponds to damage to the busy lateral region of the medulla oblongata, usually arising from occlusion of the posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA), and is termed the \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral medullary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (of Wallenberg). Its common features arise from damage to the spinothalamic tract (contralateral \u003Cem\u003Ebodily\u003C/em\u003E pain/temperature loss), spinal trigeminal (V) nucleus (ipsilateral \u003Cem\u003Efacial\u003C/em\u003E pain/temperature loss), inferior cerebellar peduncle (ataxia), nucleus ambiguus (dysphagia/dysphonia), and the inferior vestibular nucleus (of VIII; vertigo/nystagmus/diplopia/vomiting).\u003Cbr\u003E\u003Cbr\u003EThe medial medullary syndrome (of Dejerine) is distinguished by prominent contralateral corticospinal motor deficits, plus contralateral dorsal column (medial lemniscus) sensory deficits and ipsilateral hypoglossal (XII) nerve palsy. Spinal cord hemisection (Brown-S\u00e9quard syndrome) also presents with crossed deficits (ipsilateral paralysis and touch / vibration / proprioception deficits, with contralateral pain/temperature deficits), however does not involve the cranial nerves. Weber syndrome refers to basal midbrain injury that classically presents with ipsilateral oculomotor palsy and contralateral pyramidal weakness. Locked-in syndrome arises from bilateral injury to the ventral pons, and manifests as near-total paralysis, affecting the entire body except the eyes, with preserved consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Crossed signs with cranial nerve involvement suggest a brainstem pathology","The brainstem is densely packed and understanding stroke syndromes requires regular revision of the key features at each level"],"references":["Stroke syndromes and clinical management. Balami JS, Chen RL, Buchan AM. QJM. 2013 Jul;106(7):607-15."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"162"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/14946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-09-28T09:35:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T08:49:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28749"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"",